\begin_layout Title
Which connectivity measure is best for fMRI based cortical clustering?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Resting state fMRI (rsfMRI) provides complementary information to the sulcal
 brain anatomy about the cytoarchitecture and function of the human brain
 and therefore parcellation based on rsfMRI is becoming increasingly popular.
 A number of recent papers have presented cortical parcellation methods
 based on functional connectivity which is measured through correlation
 of fMRI time series from a ROI or point to the rest of the brain.
 In this paper, we present a new connectivity measure based on geodesic
 distance on unit sphere.
 We also point out that the popularly used connectivity feature based on
 spatial correlation, even though expensive in terms of computation, contains
 redundancies and does not perform well in quantitative evaluation.
 Additionally, we compare the proposed and other connectivity measures,
 and analyze their relationships to each other.
 We demonstrate that the connectivity measure based on geodesic distance
 on sphere leads to more consistent parcellation acorss and within subject.
 This measure also shows superior performance with respect to the number
 of samples required for parcellation.
\end_layout

